{# ===== SUB-SHAPE 1 · GLOSSARY INDEX — related-grid term list (from /glossary/) ===== #}
<section class="section" id="kitchen-sink-b3-listing-hub-glossary-terms">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Browse the terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Browse the glossary.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Every entry is a real, plain-English definition &mdash; what the term means, why it matters, and where it comes up. More terms are added regularly.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="related-grid">
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/bank-reconciliation/">
        <h3>Bank reconciliation</h3>
        <p>Matching your books to your bank statement for the period so the balances agree &mdash; the core accuracy control in bookkeeping.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/chart-of-accounts/">
        <h3>Chart of accounts</h3>
        <p>The structured list of every account your books record into &mdash; the framework every report is built on.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/double-entry-accounting/">
        <h3>Double-entry accounting</h3>
        <p>Every transaction recorded as equal debits and credits, so the books always balance &mdash; the foundation of reliable accounting.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/general-ledger/">
        <h3>General ledger</h3>
        <p>The complete record of every transaction posted to every account &mdash; the books&rsquo; source of truth.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/accrual-vs-cash-basis-accounting/">
        <h3>Accrual vs. cash basis accounting</h3>
        <p>Cash records money when it moves; accrual records it when earned or owed &mdash; and the choice changes what your reports say.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/catch-up-bookkeeping/">
        <h3>Catch-up bookkeeping</h3>
        <p>Bringing months or years of un-entered books current &mdash; distinct from cleanup, which fixes books that were kept wrong.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/month-end-close/">
        <h3>Month-end close</h3>
        <p>The monthly routine that finalizes the books so the period&rsquo;s numbers are complete and trustworthy.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/accounts-receivable/">
        <h3>Accounts receivable</h3>
        <p>Money customers owe you for work already delivered &mdash; an asset until it&rsquo;s collected.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/accounts-payable/">
        <h3>Accounts payable</h3>
        <p>Money you owe vendors for bills received but not yet paid &mdash; a liability until settled.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/trial-balance/">
        <h3>Trial balance</h3>
        <p>A list of every account&rsquo;s balance confirming total debits equal total credits &mdash; the books&rsquo; internal-consistency check.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/profit-and-loss-statement/">
        <h3>Profit and loss statement</h3>
        <p>Revenue minus expenses over a period &mdash; whether you made money, and where it came from and went.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/balance-sheet/">
        <h3>Balance sheet</h3>
        <p>A point-in-time snapshot of what you own, owe, and are worth &mdash; assets = liabilities + equity.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/fractional-cfo/">
        <h3>Fractional CFO</h3>
        <p>Senior financial leadership part-time &mdash; the forecasting and judgment a full-time CFO gives, without the full-time cost.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/sales-tax-nexus/">
        <h3>Sales tax nexus</h3>
        <p>The connection to a state that requires you to collect its sales tax &mdash; physical or, post-Wayfair, economic.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/bookkeeping-vs-accounting/">
        <h3>Bookkeeping vs. accounting</h3>
        <p>Bookkeeping records and reconciles; accounting interprets and advises &mdash; what each is, and who you need.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/cost-of-goods-sold/">
        <h3>Cost of goods sold</h3>
        <p>The direct cost of what you sold &mdash; and getting it right is the difference between knowing your margin and guessing.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/cash-flow-statement/">
        <h3>Cash flow statement</h3>
        <p>Actual cash in and out over a period &mdash; the statement that explains &lsquo;profitable but broke.&rsquo;</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/depreciation/">
        <h3>Depreciation</h3>
        <p>Spreading an asset&rsquo;s cost over its useful life &mdash; a non-cash expense that lowers profit, not cash.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/certified-quickbooks-proadvisor/">
        <h3>Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor</h3>
        <p>What the ProAdvisor credential means &mdash; and what it doesn&rsquo;t (it&rsquo;s not Intuit affiliation, not a CPA).</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/retained-earnings/">
        <h3>Retained earnings</h3>
        <p>Cumulative profit the business has kept &mdash; an equity account each year&rsquo;s net income rolls into.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/deferred-revenue/">
        <h3>Deferred revenue</h3>
        <p>Money collected before the work is delivered &mdash; a liability until earned, not income on receipt.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/opening-balance/">
        <h3>Opening balance</h3>
        <p>An account&rsquo;s starting balance &mdash; the foundation everything else is built on, and a top cause of wrong books after a migration.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/1099-vs-w2/">
        <h3>1099 vs. W-2</h3>
        <p>Employee vs. independent contractor &mdash; the classification that drives withholding, taxes, and real compliance risk.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/journal-entry/">
        <h3>Journal entry</h3>
        <p>The double-entry record of a transaction &mdash; debits and credits; manual adjusting entries close the books.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/accrued-expenses/">
        <h3>Accrued expenses</h3>
        <p>Costs incurred but not yet paid or billed &mdash; a liability recorded by adjusting entries on accrual books.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/prepaid-expenses/">
        <h3>Prepaid expenses</h3>
        <p>Payments made in advance &mdash; recorded as an asset, then expensed over the period they cover.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/fixed-assets/">
        <h3>Fixed assets</h3>
        <p>Long-lived tangible property &mdash; equipment, vehicles, buildings &mdash; capitalized and depreciated, not expensed at purchase.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/operating-expenses/">
        <h3>Operating expenses</h3>
        <p>The ongoing costs of running the business not tied to a sale &mdash; below gross profit on the P&L.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/owners-equity/">
        <h3>Owner&rsquo;s equity</h3>
        <p>The owner&rsquo;s residual claim on the business &mdash; assets minus liabilities, the equity section of the balance sheet.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/owners-draw/">
        <h3>Owner&rsquo;s draw</h3>
        <p>Money an owner takes out of an unincorporated business for personal use &mdash; it reduces equity, and it isn&rsquo;t payroll or a deductible expense.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/working-capital/">
        <h3>Working capital</h3>
        <p>Current assets minus current liabilities &mdash; the short-term cushion that funds day-to-day operations.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/gross-margin/">
        <h3>Gross margin</h3>
        <p>Gross profit as a percentage of revenue &mdash; how much of each sales dollar is left after COGS.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/write-off/">
        <h3>Write-off</h3>
        <p>Removing an uncollectible or worthless amount from the books and recording the loss &mdash; not the same as a tax deduction.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/net-income/">
        <h3>Net income</h3>
        <p>Revenue minus all expenses over a period &mdash; the final profit on the P&L, and not the same as cash.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/amortization/">
        <h3>Amortization</h3>
        <p>Spreading the cost of an intangible asset, or a loan&rsquo;s principal, over time &mdash; depreciation&rsquo;s intangible counterpart.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/undeposited-funds/">
        <h3>Undeposited Funds</h3>
        <p>The default QuickBooks holding account where received payments wait until you group them into a deposit that matches the bank &mdash; and a classic place errors pile up.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/class-tracking/">
        <h3>Class tracking</h3>
        <p>The QuickBooks feature for tagging transactions to a segment &mdash; location, department, program &mdash; so you can run a P&L by class. Powerful, but only if applied consistently.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/bank-feeds/">
        <h3>Bank feeds</h3>
        <p>The QuickBooks feature that auto-imports transactions from a connected bank or card into the For Review queue. Speeds bookkeeping &mdash; but matching the feed is not a finished reconciliation.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/audit-trail/">
        <h3>Audit trail</h3>
        <p>QuickBooks&rsquo; built-in, unalterable log of every change to the file &mdash; who did what, and when. Essential for accountability and for finding what changed.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/memorized-transaction/">
        <h3>Memorized transaction</h3>
        <p>A saved template QuickBooks uses to create repeating transactions on a schedule &mdash; recurring invoices, bills, journal entries. Saves time; stale templates post wrong amounts.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/w-9-form/">
        <h3>Form W-9</h3>
        <p>The form you collect from a contractor to get their taxpayer ID &mdash; so you can issue a 1099 at year end. Educational only.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/1099-nec/">
        <h3>Form 1099-NEC</h3>
        <p>The form that reports $600+ paid to a contractor in a year &mdash; we get the QuickBooks data right; your CPA files. Educational only.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/ein/">
        <h3>Employer Identification Number (EIN)</h3>
        <p>The IRS&rsquo;s nine-digit federal tax ID for a business &mdash; like an SSN for the entity. Educational only; the IRS issues it.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/estimated-taxes/">
        <h3>Estimated taxes</h3>
        <p>Quarterly payments on income that isn&rsquo;t withheld &mdash; the pay-as-you-go system. Your CPA calculates them; accurate books make the estimate reliable.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/payroll-liabilities/">
        <h3>Payroll liabilities</h3>
        <p>What you&rsquo;ve withheld from employees or owe as an employer but haven&rsquo;t yet remitted &mdash; a liability until it&rsquo;s paid, and the trust-fund portion is serious.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="related-card" href="/glossary/fiscal-year/">
        <h3>Fiscal year</h3>
        <p>The 12-month period a business reports on &mdash; often the calendar year, but not always. It sets when the books close and returns come due.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

